value.value: One of a group of four short muscles in the hand that originate on the radial and ulnar sides of the tendons of the flexor digitorum profundus and insert in the radial lateral band of the extensor expansion tendon; they are involved in the extension of the proximal and distal interphalangeal joints, and are supplied by the median and ulnar nerves and the palmar metacarpal arteries.

A muscle that originates on the distal border of the flexor retinaculum and the tubercles of the scaphoid and trapezium, and inserts into the lateral aspect of the first metacarpal; it is involved in the rotation and flexion of the thumb and is supplied by the recurrent branch of the medial nerve and the superficial palmar branch of the radial artery.

A muscle that originates on the distal anteriomedial surface of the ulna and inserts in the distal anteriolateral surface of the radius; it is involved in the pronation of the forearm and is supplied by the anterior interosseous nerve and artery.
The skin or integument covering the buttocks.
The skin or integument covering the thigh.
The determination of the amount of glutamate dehydrogenase produced by Clostridium difficile present in a sample.

label.value: Clostridium difficile A and/or B Toxin Measurement

value.value: The determination of the amount of A and/or B toxin produced by Clostridium difficile present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of tcdA DNA produced by Clostridium difficile present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of tcdB DNA produced by Clostridium difficile present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of tcdC DNA produced by Clostridium difficile present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of the Clostridium difficile species that is considered toxigenic in a biological sample.
The determination of the amount of A toxin produced by Clostridium difficile present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of B toxin produced by Clostridium difficile present in a sample.
The determination of the amount of the strain of Clostridium difficile species that produces Toxin B in a biological sample.
The determination of the amount of cdt DNA produced by Clostridium difficile present in a sample.
An adjudicator performing the assessment that is given the designation of one.
An adjudicator performing the assessment that is given the designation of two.
An adjudicator performing the assessment that is given the designation of three.

A technique for calculating cardiac output using a Swan-Ganz catheter that is inserted into the pulmonary artery through a peripheral vein to measure the change in right ventricular outflow blood temperature after a cold saline solution is injected into the right atrium from a proximal catheter port.
A non-invasive technique that utilizes abdominal skin electrodes and computerized spectral analysis to assess gastric myoelectrical activity.
A technique for measuring microscopic optical density on exposed film or photographic images through the detection of faint spectral lines.
A method of empirically measuring the velocity and attenuation of ultrasonic sound waves as they pass through tissue.

A technique for measuring anatomical densities in which a single X-ray beam, whose low and high energy is separated, is aimed at the bone or tissue of interest and x-ray absorption is assessed. This technique has multiple applications including the measurement of bone mineral density and bone mineral content and more novel applications such as breast density.
A technique used to measure the skin induration diameter of intradermal tuberculin tests based on resistance to the movement of a ballpoint pen across the skin.
An in vitro assay that utilizes live cells to test the biological activity or potency of a drug substance or product.
A species of mold fungus in the phylum Ascomycota that is commonly found in soil. This species is a rare opportunistic pathogen in humans.
A subspecies of Staphylococcus capitis that is positive for urease activity and is able to produce acid from maltose aerobically.
Any species, subspecies, or strain of Acinetobacter that is able to grow in the presence of carbapenem.
A species of slow-growing non-photochromogenic bacteria in the genus Mycobacterium. This species is a frequent cause of nontuberculous lung infections in norther Europe.

A species of slow-growing, nontuberculous bacteria in the genus Mycobacterium. This species is able to cause opportunistic lung infections and extrapulmonary or disseminated disease in immunocompromised individuals.
A subspecies of Mycobacterium abscessus. M. abcessus subsp. massiliense has a truncated erm(41) gene and is susceptible to clarithromycin.

A subspecies of Mycobacterium abscessus. M. abscessus subsp. bolletii is recognized as a rare pathogen with a functional inducible erythromycin ribosome methyltransferase (erm) (41) gene and macrolide resistance.

label.value: Subject Met Eligibility Criteria But Was Not Needed

value.value: An indication that the individual met inclusion and exclusion criteria but was ultimately not utilized as a trial subject.
A dependent position where the legs of a subject dangle or hang down while sitting.

An individual's biological or non-biological first generation offspring, including but not limited to biological children (including those born outside of marriage), adopted children, step children, and foster children.
A female progeny with genetic makeup inherited from the parent.
A male progeny with genetic makeup inherited from the parent.
Administration through perfusion liquid.
The fluid that is abnormally collected in localized areas of damaged tissue within the body, usually composed of living and dead white blood cells, bacteria, and dead tissue.
The gas located in the alveolus of the lungs, which takes part in gas exchange with the blood in the pulmonary capillaries.

The watery fluid, consisting of vulvar gland, endometrium, and oviduct secretions, cervical mucus, vaginal wall plasma transudate, exfoliated cells, and bacterial and immune cell products, that hydrates and forms an antimicrobial barrier for the mucosa of the lower female genital tract.
The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a serum or plasma sample.
The liquid lying above a liquid, solid or semi-solid residue, which is separated by crystallization, precipitation or centrifugation of a cerebrospinal fluid sample.
A heterogeneous and variable aggregate of body fluids, tissues, cells, microorganisms, and other materials that are collected from a swab biospecimen collection procedure.

label.value: Overall Tracer Uptake Compared to Nadir

value.value: A visually assessed combination of extent and intensity of tracer uptake, as compared to nadir.
The identification of an organ that may contain a tumor, lesion or site of disease, and may be part of the objective assessment of the response to the therapeutic intervention.
